Civil Rights Group Warns of Travel to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black people traveling to Missouri against state discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group said in a statement: "The NAACP travel statement issued for Missouri State, effective until August 28, 2017, calls on all African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to be particularly vigilant and extremely cautious when moving around the state given a series of suspicious race-based events that have recently occurred across the state and are listed here."
According to the NAACP, the group was urged to issue a travel warning by both a recent Missouri law that makes it harder to win discrimination-related lawsuits, and the fact that state law enforcement targets unequally largely minorities.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They are pulled to the edge of the road because of the color of their skin, they are beaten or killed," said Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri branch of the NAACP, to The Kansas City Star newspaper.
"We've never received complaints that close before."
This is the first such warning issued by the organization for the U.S. state.
The group cited events such as racist insults against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black student from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while driving through the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with the crime.
In addition, the note points to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General that shows that black drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped in the state than white drivers.
"The note is designed to make people aware and alert their families, friends, and coworkers to what might happen in Missouri," said Chapel.
"People need to be prepared, whether it's to bring bail money or to inform relatives that they're going through the state."
Based on the latest data from the FBI’s Hate Crime Reporting Program, 100 hate crimes were documented in Missouri in 2015, ranking the state 16th in terms of the number of hate crimes committed across the state.
The travel warning is also in response to Missouri's new law making it difficult for the company to sue for discrimination in seeking housing or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel notes for Texas and Arizona after those states passed immigration laws obliging local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations because, according to the ACLU, this increases racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently interest groups have begun using this measure in response to certain U.S. domestic laws and trends.
Hepatitis: what should everyone know about the different forms of this difficult disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different hepatitis A, B, C, D and E viruses.
All these viruses cause acute inflammation of the liver tissue.
However, chronic hepatitis B and C can progress to liver cirrhosis, i.e. wrinkled liver and liver cancer.
Kuulo Kutsar, an epidemiology adviser at the Health Board, says that the signs of acute hepatitis are the same for all types of hepatitis – fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, greyish stools, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
The latter also comes from the popular name of inflammation of the liver, jaundice.
In children, hepatitis can progress without symptoms.
Different types of liver inflammation can only be determined from laboratory data.
Acute hepatitis can transition to chronic hepatitis and go on for decades without symptoms, which means that a person may not know anything about his or her dangerous liver-damaging disease.
Kuuso Kutsar brings out different forms of hepatitis and describes their course in more detail.
Hepatitis A viruses spread from a sick person and infect us by eating contaminated food or drinking water, having sex, passing stools from hands and hands to food, surfaces, objects, entering the mouth, and using drugs.
The risk group of hepatitis A infection includes the family members and caregivers of the patient, people with chronic liver disease, people who have sex with the infected person, men who have sex with men, drug addicts, travellers to countries with high prevalence of hepatitis A.
The infection can be prevented by vaccination, especially for people who travel a lot and are at risk for hepatitis A.
In addition, it is important to comply with daily hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before using them for food.
Hepatitis B viruses are spread by contact with the blood of a sick person, injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated household items (tooth brushes, shaving tools), having sex with a donor blood, having sex with a person suspected of having hepatitis, and having hepatitis from a sick mother to a fetus/newborn child.
The risk group for hepatitis B infection includes injecting drug users, sex partners of an infected person, men who have sex with men, the newborn of an infected mother, family members and caregivers of a sick person, health care workers exposed to blood and other body fluids, rescue workers and police officers, and travellers visiting countries with high rates of hepatitis B.
It is possible to vaccinate people to prevent hepatitis B; in particular, it is recommended to vaccinate people at risk, as well as people with chronic liver disease, HIV infection, sexually transmitted diseases and diabetes.
Other preventive measures for hepatitis B include: avoiding the use of foreign hygiene and manicure products, other sharp tools and needles, tattooing and piercing, and the use of condoms in case of constipated sex or avoiding sexual risk behaviour.
Vaccination against hepatitis B is part of the national immunisation programme in Estonia and is free of charge for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are spread by contact with the blood of a sick person, injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated household items, having sex with a donor blood, having sex with a person suspected of having hepatitis, and from a sick mother to a fetus/newborn child.
The risk group for hepatitis C infection includes injecting drug users, sex partners of an infected person, men who have sex with men, the newborn of an infected mother, family members and caregivers of a sick person, health care workers exposed to blood and other body fluids, rescue workers and police officers, HIV-infected persons, and travellers visiting countries with high rates of hepatitis C.
The preventive measures for hepatitis C are: avoiding the use of foreign hygiene and manicure products, other sharp tools and needles, tattooing and piercing, and the use of condoms in case of infectious sex.
There is no vaccine for hepatitis C.
Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which multiplies in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
Because of this, hepatitis D infection occurs with hepatitis B or as a superinfection in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
Hepatitis D viruses are spread by contact with blood and other body fluids, contaminated syringes and needles, sexually and infrequently from infected mother to fetus.
The risk group for hepatitis D is chronic hepatitis B virus carriers and people with no immunity against hepatitis B.
An effective preventive measure is vaccination with a hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects a person from becoming infected with the hepatitis D virus.
Hepatitis E viruses are spread by faecal-oral route through drinking water and food, including low heat-treated beef, fish and clams, donor blood, shared syringes, and from infected mother to fetus.
Passengers can become infected in countries with high rates of hepatitis E.
Preventive measures for hepatitis E are compliance with hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands after going to the toilet, before cooking and eating, after taking care of the sick.
Wash fruits and vegetables before consumption, avoid eating a little cooked beef, fish and seafood, drink only safe drinking water, and avoid using drugs.
