Blocking critics from Facebook do not run for state office if you do not tolerate criticism from voters
The father of our country knew a lot about unfavorable media coverage.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn’t take long for the newspapers to beat him up for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he did not force his critics to remain silent.
Because in 1783, Washington said that "freedom of speech could be taken away from us, and silently and silently we could be led to slaughter like sheep."
That brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who has to work hard to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
Earlier this week, he was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU).
The governor's office dismissed the lawsuit, and online commentaries abounded with counter-reactions in the style of "Who Cares?".
"It's just Facebook," many said.
But it does matter.
And it matters a lot when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is an incredibly popular Republican governor in an overwhelmingly Democratic state.
His approval rating is the second-best among the country's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a thoughtless, responsive figurehead.
He has led the state with a firm hand and he has remained firm on his principles.
In addition, he has used Facebook rather skillfully as a key tool in his dealings with his constituents, for example, by presenting his bald head cheerfully for the first time since chemotherapy.
Thus, the Governor's Page, an official-labeled public forum operated by staff paid by taxpayers' dollars to block visiting people, is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan’s spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor’s behavior, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it’s too easy to paint a picture of online trolls, spammers, or angry crowds.
The Post had a conversation with several real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And that's exactly what they are, real people who communicate with their elected leaders, a teacher, a business owner and a pastor, not Internet trolls.
They all said that their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not obscene.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, emphasising Hogan's Catholicism.
Lakshmi Sarma Ramani, a lawyer from Bowie, Maryland, did not incite anger, but real hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed because he has not responded to hate crimes or other recent news," he wrote in The Post's news story in the comment section.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people comment on the same topic, someone will immediately call it a ‘collective effort’ instead of acknowledging that it’s a large group of concerned citizens.”
What the governor's office called a "targeted spam attack," others would probably call "public support."
The Facebook era allows messages to be easily matched by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It is much cleaner than it used to be when workers had to be sent out to collect newspapers with critical editorials and burn them or arrest the protesters and shut them up.
But that’s exactly what’s happening right now, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for flouting Facebook and other social media channels.
President Trump has sued Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first landmark judgments on the subject was made last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris ruled in Alexandria that the chairwoman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment to the Constitution when she blocked a voter from her Facebook page.
In Kentucky, the ACLU also visited Governor Matt Bevin (R) for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s time, affordable postage had a similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous writers thumped his way of running.
And even then, Washington had to deal with anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to newspapers under pseudonyms such as Yuricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, leveling Washington's decisions.
According to historical documents collected by the online George Washington Letter Collection Project, his office was buried under petitions criticizing his views on friendship, trade, and shipping deals with Britain.
But he didn't make them keep quiet.
Freedom of expression, dissent and debate are the foundations of our country.
And proper management means accepting it.
