Poverty and death in Indonesia’s gold-rich land
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a stove.
He rarely even uses the pot.
In a wooden cabin in the rugged Papuan province of Paniai, the capital of Enarotali, a housewife places a batat called a nota in the local language right on the fire.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is taken from the fire and eagerly eaten with unwashed hands.
Degei sits on a muddy floor without any furniture, where he does his daily chores, such as washing with cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet role is filled by a bucket in a room without a roof.
Being the youngest of her husband's four wives, she is not assigned to care for any of the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
However, working late can be dangerous most of the men in the village are unemployed and many of them drink heavily, plus there are soldiers here.
"Nobody dares to visit after five o'clock in the evening," he says.
It is a rare sighting of the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed by Indonesia in 1969 following a controversial referendum that saw only 1,026 elderly people forced to vote before the eyes of the occupying forces.
The movement, which was pushing the Dutch out of power, quickly turned its fury against the Jakarta government, which is still keeping the region under its strong control, keeping away foreign journalists and human rights monitors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, leaving the eastern part of the island to independent Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is both a remote and an abandoned place. To get here, you need to fly from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire for 90 minutes and then go on a five-hour trek in a rental car.
There is no public transport.
With a population of about 19,000, the city is made up of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and covered by corrugated iron roofs, whose rust has turned different shades of yellow-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made the journey here, not to mention journalists, and hardly any foreigners have come here.
Before the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the papaya of Honey Pago worshiped a god called Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
“We weren’t used to wearing clothes like that,” says Degei, referring to his colorful hand-woven turban, dark blouse, and bright skirt.
"Before that, we only wore plant leaves on our body."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of people living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy statistics are among the worst in Asia.
But it is also a gold-rich country in Indonesia.
Just 100 km from Paniai, a mountainous province about the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000, Grasberg is the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, owned by Freeport McMoran, a Phoenix-based company.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about US$3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua can boast supplies of hardwood, worth an estimated US$78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of papaya suffering as they result in the suffocating presence of a powerful Indonesian military.
A 2005 study by The New York Times showed that Freeport paid approximately US$20 million to local military and military units between 1998 and 2004, including up to US$150,000 to one officer.
Papuans' efforts to ensure greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are ruthlessly manipulated.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the mass killing in the highlands belonging to the Papuan tribes in the 1970s was a measure of genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested over 3,900 peaceful protesters in the area.
The Birsbane archdiocese's 2016 report "We Are Losing Everything" includes testimonies of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture (according to another report, rape and electrocution are particularly common) and brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"The number of victims is hard to count because such incidents happen every week," said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened because Papua’s natural resources have caused an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
83% of the province’s 3.5 million inhabitants are Christians, but the demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from Indonesia’s crowded islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
The Javanese family canteens sell crispy chicken and mixed-vegetable gado-gado served with peanut sauce.
The locals can't compete with them.
“Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables at a traditional market cheaper than local poppies,” explains Paniais-born 24-year-old Abeth You, who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital for work.
"Paapua mama-mamas [women], who live in oil, will therefore lose their market share."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, pledged in his 2014 election campaign to address these inequalities and human rights violations in Papua.
The former carpenter won 27 of Papua's 29 constituencies, including Paniai, on his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta.
But very little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokow in the expectation that he will live up to our hopes of restoring justice," You says.
In fact, just two months after Jokowi took office in October, Paniai was in a slump.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children in Enarotali sang Christmas carols at a fire when two Indonesian soldiers appeared on a motorcycle out of darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and eyewitnesses, the drunken soldiers chased the children and beat them with the handles of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at the children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so cruelly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby Electoral Commission building was set on fire, and things escalated further the next day.
Around 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered at the football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting vibes and performed a waita-dance of the Papuan honey pago tribe, during which a circle was run and a bird song was imitated.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and military personnel.
"If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," according to an official document seen by TIME magazine, but not issued to local media outlets.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, an elder in the Kego Koto district of the city of Enarotal, sensed the impending threat and called for peace by asking the crowd to go home.
No one had the will to listen.
"Turning around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist," he told TIME magazine in his bright colors on the porch of a tree house.
Kayame still doesn't know who the shooter was, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“It was a lot of people,” he added.
Local man Alfius Youw was shot three times, according to his cousin.
“I ran over to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Yohanes told TIME magazine.
"I saw that he was dead...I kissed him."
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his subordinates only ensured the security of their precinct as it was attacked.
“We must protect ourselves if we are to be killed,” said Pudjo Sulistiyo, a Papuan police spokesman.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many injured.
The news of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura where he expressed condolences to the families of the victims and promised to address the abuses in Papua.
"I want to solve this case immediately so that it will never happen again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, the Minister of Security Wiranto said that he would establish an out-of-court mechanism to resolve the crimes against human rights that occurred.
There were excuses almost immediately.
"Most of the crimes happened a long time ago.
Some of these occurred in the 1990s and early 2000s.
“The point is that we are committed to solving these crimes, but we have to follow certain processes,” he said.
Speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, Wiranto retracted his remarks, saying he had no intention of creating a mechanism in Papua to deal with complaints.
Instead, he said that "everything will be resolved by law".
Wiranto, who has been accused by the UN of crimes against human rights in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people in East Timor during the 1999 bloody independence referendum, said that 11 crimes against human rights have already been solved in Papua, including what happened in Paniai.
The families of the victims of Paniai accepted such claims with gloomy distrust.
"I've been interrogated four times in the last three years, but no progress has been made," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
He says he still lives in fear years later.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid the military will arrest me, I'm afraid I'll be shot."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the opinion that the Paniai people are afraid to dissect this incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury the four victims.
"After burying the bodies, the military came looking for me," he says.
The shootings haven't stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot dead villagers in Paniai's neighboring district of Deiyai.
One person was killed and 17 wounded, including children, as a result of a dispute between villagers and the manager of a construction company, who refused to transport the unconscious man to the hospital.
The man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested at the construction site in front of the company's office.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at the policemen, to which the latter responded with warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian military police) started shooting at the crowd, killing one person.
“We were in a big panic, we were afraid of revenge,” said 29-year-old Domingo Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the injuries.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament has called for the police officers involved to be held accountable and for the police mobile brigade to be pulled back from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development feeds the discontent of the honey, mon, dan and damal tribes living in Papua's verdant central highlands.
Many of them have joined the rebel army of the Free Papuan Movement (VPL), which claims to protect the rights of the Papuans by organising sporadic attacks and kidnappings among Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the leaders of the VPL are from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, under the pretext of "protecting national sovereignty", the military has arrested Paniais in recent years and arbitrarily detained thousands of people.
Some of them will never show up again.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is known as a "tragic forgotten place".
Poverty breeds discontent.
The lack of rice sold in Enarotal is too expensive for locals to buy.
Bread is just as inaccessible.
People grow all their food by themselves mainly sweet potatoes, plus a little fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, the rest being sold at the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has deepened between indigenous Papuans and new migrants who have been arriving in large numbers since the opening of new routes to Nabire Airport.
The few jobs that exist go to better educated and wealthier migrants.
Papuans themselves often lack the capital or the necessary skills to run a competitive business.
“Young people are not interested in staying because there are neither jobs nor money,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps the world's eyes off Papua.
In addition, there are severe restrictions on foreign media.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua because "they did not observe the relevant practices", although they had been granted a rare filming permit.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy head of the Asia Division of Human Rights Watch, Jokowi's election promises to lift restrictions on reporting to promote transparency and development have not been implemented.
"Journalists attempting to report on Indonesia from the most easterly troubled provinces of Papua and West Papua face new risks of visa rejection and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of a piercing glance from the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua's close neighbours.
In March, six Pacific countries, Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands, urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "miscellaneous large-scale crimes" in Papua, including the shooting of Paniai.
These same countries have historically supported the VPL.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the group's allegations, telling journalists in Jakarta: "Indonesia still has democratic order and freedom of the press, so evidence of human rights cases would be hard to bury."
Local people want more foreign governments to pay attention.
When a Dutch delegation led by the country’s human rights envoy Kees Van Baar visited Jayapura on May 4, locals broke their silence, saying they wanted to remain anonymous, urging: “We want freedom.”
Indonesia will hold a new presidential election in 2019, but the Papuans do not believe they will vote for Jokow again.
"Jokowi is a man of good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting," says tribal council chairman Hobai.
He wants Jokow to understand that, in addition to living under constant threat from the predatory military, the Paniai people are suffering from poor education and health services.
According to Gobai, the Paniai people, like other Papuans, consider their vote to be a debt to be paid.
"They don't need money, they want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of Paniai’s shooting victims survived the final symbolic insurrection by burying the body of one of the victims in a land opposite the police station and the military base.
Knowing that justice may never be done, at least they will not let those responsible forget their crimes.
"One of our family members was killed," Yacobus says with his head lowered.
"What else can we do?"
