“The Ukrainian community has always been big in Estonia, and due to the complicated conditions in the country, it is natural that people are looking for work and study opportunities in a country where the community and many of the family are already ahead,” said Kristin Rammus, a spokeswoman for the Ministry of the Interior.
Last year and last year, the number of Ukrainians granted temporary residence permits was even higher than the number of Russian citizens, although in the last ten years the number of temporary residence permits issued to the latter has increased.
When Ukrainians come here to work, Russian citizens come here for family migration.
