New results of age assessment tests for asylum seekers in Sweden published
In Sweden, a test was carried out to assess the age of asylum seekers using a novel medical approach. The latest results show that more than 80 percent of those tested were older than 18, but not all believe in the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Institute of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinealverket) started testing earlier this year.
The tests were created to assess the age of asylum seekers more accurately after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to correctly determine the age of several allegedly underage refugees.
To date, 6,880 cases have been sent for testing by Migrationsverket, and between mid-March and 31 July 2017, the Institute of Forensic Medicine has issued a total of 2,481 test results.
Eighty percent (2002) were rated 18 or older, and in another 25 cases, the Institute of Forensic Medicine estimated that the testee "could be 18 or older."
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the person was "presumably younger than 18".
The tests are only used if the person's age is in question.
Johan Göransson, who works at the Institute of Forensic Medicine, said that the results were consistent compared to previous months.
"We don't see much difference from previous months' statistics, the numbers are quite consistent," he told The Local newspaper.
The fact that a large proportion of cases were rated as over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers have lied about their age.
The institute issued 581 test results in May and said that in 442 cases "there are indications that the person being studied is 18 years of age or older".
But when the Svenska Dagbladet newspaper looked at the results of their 581 tests, it turned out that in 243 cases the person had directly claimed to be 18 this year.
This medical method of age assessment, which involves X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI of the knee joints, after which they are allowed to be analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some circles.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose job involves assessing people's biological maturity to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
"I've had good reason to think about it and I don't think the measurement method we're currently using should be used.
Determination of biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say for sure, then we shouldn't pretend we can," he told the Metro newspaper.
But Johan Göransson from the Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: "Generally speaking, the risk of inaccurately categorizing a child into adulthood is low.
The risk is highest at around 10% if the person is just under 18.
