The electric car revolution will dramatically change the demand for metals.
Who are the winners and losers?
Not only will the electric car revolution change everything from fuel to infrastructure, it will also create new winners and losers in the metal market.
While mining giants like Glencore can say that they will win in one place and lose in another, smaller mining companies won’t be helped.
Glencore currently earns from coal and oil, but there will be increasing demand for cobalt, lithium, copper, aluminum and nickel in the age of electric cars.
This year, the governments of the United Kingdom, France and Norway have stepped up their efforts to ban the sale of new cars using fossil fuels in the coming decades.
As a result, Volvo has announced that it plans to abandon its internal combustion engine and Tesla will launch a cheaper Model 3 electric car.
According to Bloomberg New Energy Finance, electric cars are expected to sell more in two decades than oil-fuelled cars.
"For some metals, it changes everything," Simona Gambranini, a raw material analyst at Capital Economics, told Bloomberg.
We have already seen a huge impact on metals such as cobalt and lithium, whose demand has been growing for years.
Electric cars have about three times more copper than conventional cars, Glencore reported.
More copper is needed at charging stations, which is why Exane BNP Paribas estimates that this will increase copper demand by about five percent by 2025.
The increase in demand for electric car batteries means additional demand for lithium, cobalt, graphite and manganese.
Glencore will benefit from rising electric car prices and being the world’s largest cobalt producer, according to Jefferies Group.
According to this brokerage firm, the other winners of the electric car race are Freeport-McMoRan and First Quantum Minerals.
The market is already responding to the changing trend.
This year, the London Metal Exchange has seen a cobalt appreciation of 70 percent.
The price increase was 37%.
The price of copper has also risen 14 percent this year, mainly due to economic growth.
Shares of Glencore rose 20 percent in London after surpassing rivals Rio Tinto Group, BHP Billiton and Anglo American.
On the losing side, there are lead companies like Recyclex and Campine that need to adapt to the new era.
The main end-use of lead is batteries that supply power to starters in petrol and diesel cars.
Electric cars use lithium-ion batteries.
"This is a serious risk to lead demand unless other uses are found that could overcome the decline in demand," said Michael Widmer, head of metal market analysis at Bank of America Merrill Lynch.
The effect of the unfolding trend is yet to be seen in the price movement of lead.
Lead has risen 17 percent this year, making it the best metal among the top industrial metals in London.
Investors see problems with metal only in the distant future.
"I'm not sure it's that bad for lead because cheap oil keeps conventional cars competitive," said Herwig Schmidt, sales manager at Triland Metals, a metal brokerage firm.
When the demand for lead drops, it occurs slowly.
This may happen in about 10 years.
In the meantime, stricter emission standards mean that demand for hybrid cars will increase, depending on lead-based batteries that are developed during frequent engine launches, according to an international lead and zinc research organization.
Light metals such as aluminium replace steel because a lighter car can travel farther with less electricity.
This explains the additional 1.6 million tonnes of alumina demand already in 2013-2016.
This represents 2.7 percent of the world’s aluminium production.
This trend is likely to intensify, Widmer said.
The price of aluminium has risen 13 percent this year, as growing demand from car manufacturers has led to a market deficit.
Steel producers don't sleep.
AK Steel Holding is working with General Motors to use nanotechnology to produce lightweight car bodies.
ArcelorMittal and Tata Steel Europe are also working to develop a lighter alloy steel to resist aluminum.
"High-strength steel should be the answer to this development," said Sylvain Brunet, an analyst at Exane BNP Paribas.
There has been some success in Europe.
The end of the oil age can also bring suffering to platinum.
Last year, about half of this precious metal was used as catalysts for diesel-powered cars, said Johnson Matthey, a metal refiner.
"Many of the raw materials currently in high demand, such as oil and platinum, may not have much demand in the future," said Bernard Dahl, a raw material analyst at Natixis.
This does not mean that raw materials as a whole will become less important, but their importance will change within 15 years.
Platinum manufacturers believe there will be continued demand for diesel hybrid cars.
Marc Grynberg, CEO of Uncore, said more hybrid cars will continue to be sold in 2025 than fully electric cars.
The platinum industry’s big hope for the next 10 years is that Toyota Motor and Hyundai Motos will develop hydrogen-based cars that rely on platinum to generate electricity from hydrogen.
So far, however, this technology has not been commercially proven.
"Diesel seems to have a clear loser on the road to electric cars," Exane told BNP Paribas of Brunet.
German automakers suffered a backlash in July after a court in Stuttgart banned diesel from Mercedes-Benz and Porsche.
How football finance rules will affect Neymar's transition to Paris
The rules, designed to prevent European football clubs from spending unbridled, do not prevent Neymar from making a world-record transition from Spanish football club Barcelona to French club Paris-Saint Germain.
Any consequences for UEFA, the governing body that rules the European game and has the power to prevent teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League tournament, are still to come.
The UEFA Financial Rules for Fair Play (FFP), introduced in 2011, mean that PSG will have to prove at some point that Neymar’s transfer was financed without huge losses.
Barcelona was paid 222 million euros ($262 million) to buy the Brazilian out of his contract alone, and Neymar’s salary is set to reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some financial aspects of Neymar's transfer to the French club.
PSG will undoubtedly be able to raise such money to recruit Neymar and add to its star formation, given that the team is funded by the Qatari energy-rich ruling family.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot to recruit players, but they have to balance it with legal income sources that allow them to come out with their own in the football business.
The FFP was founded by Michel Platini after he was elected president of UEFA in 2007.
This former French player believed that clubs that would fall into great debt in search of success would actually engage in cheating and risk ruin if banks or owners had to give up support.
As of 2011, the FFP focuses on tracking the losses of clubs instead of debt.
This change means that the business model that Roman Abramovich first used in 2003 at Chelsea - to buy a club with potential and then make big spending to improve the team and create a global brand - will be more difficult to implement.
During the current three-year evaluation period of the FFP, which runs until 2018, clubs may suffer losses of up to €30 million.
And despite Platini’s disgraced rejection of the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor, Alexander Ceferin, remains committed to preventing excessive spending.
"The FFP is certainly not dead, and we will undoubtedly continue to strengthen these rules in the future," said Andrea Traverso, an FFP supervisor at UEFA.
Although PSG paid Neymar for the buy-over clause in a single payment, it is possible for them to break that amount down for accounting purposes throughout the duration of the contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so it is possible to show the transitional fee over the next five years as an annual amount of EUR 44.4 million.
For the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, PSG, along with Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City, suffered the most severe penalties.
PSG was fined €60 million ($82 million at the time), which was later reduced to €20 million, and the club was required to limit the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is looking for clubs that may try to outsmart regulatory financial institutions by blowing up their income through companies associated with club owners.
The Qatari company may sponsor PSG, but if the value of the sponsorship is considered to exceed standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to count as official income.
This was the case in 2014 when UEFA decided that the value of Qatar Tourism Authority's PSG support was poached.
It has been said that some of Neymar's PSG service may come through payments from the 2022 World Cup Management Committee from Qatar.
However, PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar could become a World Cup ambassador, and argue that UEFA regulators could easily expose such a manoeuvre.
The penalties previously imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will be even more vigilant in any attempt to circumvent the rules.
People familiar with the situation said on Thursday that UEFA had not discussed the Neymar transition with PSG in advance.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of ensuring their anonymity as they were not allowed to discuss the situation with PSG.
The latest published reports show that PSG made more than €10 million in profits in the 2015-2016 season with a turnover of around €542.4 million.
Data for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG hopes Neymar's arrival will have a positive impact on sponsorship deals, merchandising and shirt sales.
The club expects a turnover increase of at least 30 per cent in connection with the conclusion of the contract.
The Spanish league, clearly upset by the departure of one of the biggest football stars, sought to prevent Neymar's transition, claiming that PSG was thereby violating the FFP.
"This is a clear case of 'financial doping' with the club and the country," La Liga president Javier Tebas told the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to the PSG as being primarily owned by Qatar.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports magnate, shares La Liga's stance on state funding for the club.
"This is a consequence of property rights and has completely changed the entire football landscape over the past 15 years," Wenger said.
"If the club belongs to the state, anything is possible.
It is very difficult to respect the financial rules of fair play, as a country may have other ways or other interests for such a large player to represent the country."
