The secret of clean beaches: night cleaning and poor beach weather
Colder summer weather also means less cleaning effort on the beaches of Tallinn.
“If there is no water, there are people on the beach, and if there are no people, there are no people on the beach.”
Seagulls cry out at the North Tallinn Stroomi beach.
For them, the melodic competition lies with the low-speed tractor, which plows the stripes on the beam.
In fact, the latter sifts through the sand from a depth of seven centimetres, picking up marine debris and debris left behind by humans: bottle caps, cigarette butts, and more.
People come to the beach whether the water is hot or not.
If the weather is nice, then there are people on the beach, and if there are no people, then there are no people,” says Aleksandr Usov, the manager of the cleaning works of the private limited company Haabersti Haldus.
It’s 6:30 a.m. and the beach is busy, because at 8 p.m. the place has to be tidy for people.
Usov has been on duty since 4:00 p.m.
Besides Stroomi, he keeps an eye on Pirita, Lake Harku, Kakumäe and Pikakari beach in Paljasaare.
The amount of rubbish has decreased.
Years ago it was so much more.
People already know how to appreciate what is being done for them,” says Usov, who has been cleaning the beaches for 15 years.
Before, when something new was installed, it was already broken the next day.
Now what's on the beach is being kept.
The price of clean beach
One of the biggest works on Estonian beaches is the cleaning of sea litter, i.e. seaweed, washed ashore.
For example, on Pirita beach, 400,000 tons have to be transported during the beach season.
"It's an incredible quantity", notes Usov.
The second big category is household waste, which is all that people leave behind.
Stroomi Beach has eight large garbage cans that need to be emptied three times a week.
There is so much rubbish.
However, the colder summer weather has meant that the amount of garbage is one-fifth less than it would otherwise be.
The third category consists of abandoned objects.
They're mostly babies.
This time, Usov has shoveled out a dozen model cars from the sand.
They are waiting for the owners on the beach.
"Usually more of them come out, but this is a normal catch." Usov already knows that soon he will find them again in the sand.
The children come to the beach and pick up the toys to drown them in the sand again.
Disperse the trash
Erika Scholler, a representative of Haabersti management services, admits that the locals are disturbed by the tractor’s screening.
The noise, which lasts from night to early morning, interferes with the sleep of people in the neighborhood.
During the day, this work is impossible.
In one month, the beach must be screened twice.
"If we don't, the district will fine us," Scholler notes.
However, like Pirita, Pikakari and Pärnu, the goal is to get Stroomi beach under the international blue flag quality label.
“Compared to Europe, Estonia has a lot more work to do to maintain the beaches,” Scholler says.
We've got more adru and rocks and harder sand to sift.
However, there is less garbage on our beaches than anywhere else in Europe.
Upon hearing about the rubbish on the beach, Martin, who lives near Stroomi Beach, casually enters the discussion group of the journalist and cleaning staff, highlighting the current bottlenecks on the beach.
There's a nasty picture everywhere in the morning.
The problem is with the birds and bottle pickers who have been throwing trash bags inside out,” Martin reports.
Although it is difficult to assume that people will be able to change their behaviour, Martin hopes that the city government will do something about the rubbish bins and put covers on them, for example, to prevent at least the birds from going there.
Overall, however, Martin is pleased with the development of Stroomi Beach.
You can see the city is taking care of it.
With children's playgrounds, illuminated and freshly paved roads, it has become more pleasant.
It was once the case that roller skates could only be driven on one road,” notes Martin.
Treasure hunter's finds in Stroomi: coins, only coins
A 40-year-old Dimitri has come to take advantage of the low tide, combing the beach with a metal detector as a treasure hunter.
He does not believe that he will find anything valuable today or in the future.
The gods of the sea are not generous enough to do so.
"I've been doing this for a year and I haven't found anything of value so far," says Dmitri.
As a hobbyist, Dmitri’s treasure bag contains some euro coins, bottle caps and also dangerous nails that later throw into the trash.
Usually there are coins.
“There are no gold, rings or anything like that,” the treasure hunter says.
Bank of England to hold interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to keep interest rates at the same level as weak economic growth and a easing of inflation have dampened speculation over the rise.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish as tight household incomes put interest rates on hold.
Policymakers at the Bank’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted to keep the 6:2 rates at 0.25%, and fewer members are calling for an increase this month as slow economic growth has weakened support for the rise.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank cut its growth forecast for 2017 to 1.7% and for 2018 to 1.6% and warned that pressure on household incomes would remain as inflation is still expected to rise to close to 3% in the autumn.
At the same time, the bank also signaled that an increase in rates would be necessary in the next few years to contain inflation caused by Brexit and that higher than expected increases in credit costs may be necessary in financial markets.
Members also voted a year ago for the partial withdrawal of the mammoth package to boost the economy launched as a result of Brexit.
The bank will close a term funding scheme in February that offers cheap funding to banks, though said it is now expecting a £15 billion increase in its bid of £115 billion.
In the minutes of the decision on the rate, the bank says: "In the central forecast of the MPC, the gross domestic product (GDP) will remain weak in the near future, as the difficult situation of real household incomes will continue to have an impact on consumption."
Regarding the rates, it was reiterated that a "some tightening of the monetary policy" is needed to alleviate inflation, and to a "somewhat larger" extent than expected in the markets.
The stock market is currently forecasting a first increase in the third quarter of next year and a second increase in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that all types of jumps are gradual and limited.
The bank’s reduced growth forecasts for this and next year are comparable to the May forecasts of 1.9% and 1.7%.
The forecast for growth of 1.8% in 2018 remained.
After this news, the pound fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to US$1.31 and 0.4% to €1.11.
The decision not to make any changes has been driven by recent disappointing growth figures, which have dampened growing expectations due to an increase in GDP in the second quarter from 0.2% in the previous three months to 0.3%.
The bank says that growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will pick up slightly at the end of the year.
The bank’s latest inflation report gave little reason to rejoice to households suffering from rising inflation and poor wage growth, saying that the situation will get worse before it recovers.
It added that monetary policy cannot prevent an income shock in the next few years, but a significant recovery in wages is expected towards the end of the three-year forecast.
Due to the weak pound, the economy is also spurred by growing demand for British production, which partially compensates for lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were moved to 0.25% last August after a shocking EU referendum that caused a sudden weakening of the pound.
The bank estimates that it will probably take four years to fully breathe life into prices and the economy.
Before the bank's last decision, there was a sense of increasing demand to raise the rate, as inflation had increased the pressure on distressed households; in July, three policymakers called for the rate to be raised to 0.5%.
Inflation fell to 2.6% last month, compared to 2.9% in June, although the bank said it expected it to rise again in the coming months.
The bank said the excessive growth compared to the 2% target was entirely due to a weak pound.
Andrew Montlake, head of Coreco mortgage brokers, said: “Given the recent drop in exchange rates, it seems that the mortgage market is becoming increasingly competitive again as lenders yearn for work and hope to end the year positively.
The stock market looks particularly favorable to those whose current trades are beginning to close as refinancing, often without a service fee and at a low rate, has become increasingly popular."
NHS to prescribe HIV drugs to 10,000 people
Patients will have access to "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September, following a battle in the Supreme Court over whether the NHS should fund the drug.
NHS England reported that public health now makes available an estimated 10,000 pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) tablets during the initial three-year clinical trial, which have been shown to reduce the risk of infection by approximately 86% in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the clinical trial after an appeals court upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year that the NHS was able to pay for PrEP, despite the agency's own claims that the drug should instead be funded by local authorities.
NHS England executive Simon Stevens hailed the move as a "new large-scale intervention", while the National AIDS Foundation (NAT) described it as a "turning moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to start enrolling people. More clinics will be added in October, before the programme is implemented everywhere in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medications taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Clinical trial results show that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there is a sufficient amount of certain medicines in the human body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day, or at least two hours before intercourse.
Candidates eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are infected with HIV and are not receiving treatment.
Clinicians identify eligible people who are willing to participate in a clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people, and those whose HIV-positive partner is not on antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen a family doctor there can also register their wish to participate at the local sexual health clinic participating in the programme.
The program will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to receive the drugs this week following an international tender procedure.
The goal of the clinical trial is to assess the real potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on who the drug is intended for and how it is consumed and applied in the big picture.
Stevens said, "This new large-scale intervention should complement and amplify the large-scale and increasingly successful fight against HIV transmission.
This is yet another milestone in more than three decades of fighting one of humanity's greatest health problems."
Deborah Gold, executive director of NAT, said, "This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted at those who need it and belong to a high-risk group, offers the opportunity to change England's HIV epidemic.
Since September, people at high risk of HIV in England, through this NHS-funded clinical trial, have access to a powerful new tool that is individually manageable and independent of negotiation with a partner, thereby improving many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, CEO of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said, "The priority now is to make sure that the clinical trial is launched quickly across the country and that none of those at risk of HIV are left behind.
Now that the PrEP clinical trial drug has been procured, we are on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.
Sharon Hodgson, the Public Health Shadow Minister, said, "The start of the clinical trial of PrEP is very welcome and well delayed after months of delays and dragging the government's legs.
The evidence shows how much this medicine can change the way HIV is prevented and this life-changing infection is stopped.
This clinical trial brings us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the clinical trial is deployed across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to bring us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society."
The price of electricity increased by 12% in Estonia, while it decreased in Latvia and Lithuania.
In July, the difference in the next day’s exchange price of electricity between Estonia and Latvia and Lithuania decreased to 1.94 euros, compared to 7.71 euros in June this year, Elering said.
The main reason for the price difference is the Lithuanian-Swedish connection failures.
The average exchange price of electricity in Estonia last month was 34.33 euros per megawatt-hour and the price increased by 12% compared to June.
In Latvia and Lithuania, the price fell by 5% to 36.27 euros per megawatt-hour.
In Finland, the price was 34.17 euros, while the system price of the Nord Pool power exchange was 26.37 euros per megawatt-hour.
Prices increased by 12 and 7 percent, respectively.
Between Estonia and Finland, electricity flowed to Estonia for 75 percent of the hours of the previous month and to Finland for 16 percent of the hours.
The remaining nine percent of the hours between the two countries did not take place for the next day's transactions.
Electricity moved between Estonia and Latvia 99 percent of the time from Estonia to Latvia and 73 percent of the hours had the entire transmission capacity.
According to transactions on the last trading day of July, the electricity exchange price on the Nasdaq OMX market may be around 34 euros per megawatt-hour in August and 37 euros per megawatt-hour in September.
The price of carbon dioxide, which affects the price of electricity production, increased last month and transactions were carried out at a price of 5.04-5.47 euros per ton.
Living at a height – half-floor and clever design tips have made this tiny Earls Court apartment a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker who is a passionate real estate innovator, traded her large Knightsbridge home for Earls Court's apartment in 2014.
It is located on the ground floor of Queen Anne Terrace, and Joanne's failure to pack up her bags and resell the apartment is a tribute to the new design.
“Before that, I lived on much larger land with my ex-partner in Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
"I was looking for something that would be the same price as what I offered.
I was shown this Earls Court apartment and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with it and made an offer the same day."
Since the first visit, this 93 square meter apartment has undergone a complete overhaul.
At first, it was an apartment with a single bedroom and a complex layout - to get to the bedroom, you had to walk through the kitchen. Joanne wanted to add a storage room and a half-floor to take advantage of the high ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands," he said.
He hired Erfan Azad from Duck & She, an architecture and design studio based in Notting Hill, to take advantage of the 3.8 m high ceilings and create a home that would not just be a development object, but a place where Joanne could live.
The ceiling was not high enough to add two spaces on top of each other, so it was an architectural challenge to create a half-floor where one could stand upright.
Erfan had to approach the matter creatively.
"Metal construction is quite complex," he explains.
"We had to rearrange the rooms so that they were located on top of each other without having to bend over.
It wasn’t just about building a platform, we used a steel structure to make sure the height of both the upper and lower room was right.”
This arrangement allowed Erfan to create two full-height rooms on top of each other in the room, with plenty of dramatic elements.
The half-story overlooks the glamorous living room below with its old copper-lighted Retrouvius window.
Gold furniture with a mirror surface, silver details and a retro-sounding Serge Mouille light accentuate the style of the room.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding theatricality, space and light.
Mirrors have been added at both ends of the short corridor to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the rear wall with a mirror gives the impression of a window opening into another room.
At the entrance, the mirror cabinet offers storage space for all Joanne's cutlery and glassware.
The possibility to close the kitchen part when it is not in use adds to the charm of the living room, creating an image of a more glamorous space.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
What is unique about this kitchen, however, is that it is a garage-type retractable door.
"It took a bit of design work," Erfan explains with a steel-reinforced veneered MDF door.
“It has a counterweight, so it glides very easily when you push it up.”
Thanks to the smart use of space and storage space, Joanne now has 16 extra square meters, an additional bedroom and a better apartment plan.
"After all, the floor space is what you sell - or what gives value to the property," says Erfan.
“The real estate agent enters the room in an outdated form and performs calculations based on the floor area.”
Here they have been able to increase the floor space, using high-quality materials that add luxury to the room.
“Materials are the ones you touch that help you bond emotionally with your home,” says Erfan.
"You don't fall in love with electrical cable in the wall.
It's important, but it doesn't make the tongues of the heart ring."
This shows that a good design and an increased area will help to make a fairly ordinary apartment something amazing.
In fact, they may even make you want not to leave, like Joanne did.
Dane Jensen is a bounty hunter in a Chicago skyscraper competing for a promotion.
All that matters is the amount of money earned, along with any ethics.
He sees his wife and three children only in the early morning and late evening.
In the first half of the film, I find myself thinking that this is the business version of House of Cards – even Kevin Spacey and Gerard Butler’s speech is similar.
The further the film goes, the less the frame-house element remains, and the filmmakers’ moralizing intent begins to stand out more and more.
A life-changing experience for the main character will be his son getting cancer.
A choice must be made between work and family.
An architect’s dreamy son makes his father think about the really important things in his walks to the big buildings in Chicago, such as faith, goodness, love, and not even the disaster of the Twin Towers.
After the third scene, when the son opens his father’s eyes, it feels that the filmmakers have set out to make sure that the audience will cry, because even the coldest-hearted viewer cannot hold back tears from seeing the suffering of the beloved cancer-stricken boy.
When the son falls into a coma and his situation seems hopeless, the father finally understands the immorality of his job and does a good deed to the old man looking for work.
Now I’m betting on myself – if the movie has a happy ending, I’ll reward my insight after the movie with coffee, but if I’m wrong, the screenwriter can be praised for at least one surprise.
For a moment, I suspect I’ll miss my coffee when my husband calls Dane from the hospital and he rushes slowly down the hall toward the ward.
Rather, the son is miraculously healed, and even though his father has just lost his job, it turns out to be a good thing, since now is the time to take care of the family.
I'm also very good at predicting the end of the American drama.
In truth, the film is well constructed, and all the necessary elements are there.
You can cry, you can laugh, actors are good and morality is beautiful: money is not the most important thing in life.
I guess this movie brings it in really well.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to curb the president's media consumption.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he'd be the first.
Politico writes that the White House's new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information reaching President Trump, including the news, in the hope that it will keep the boss in the water more level.
Here's an excerpt from reporter Josh Dawsey:
“When White House chief of staff John F. Kelly first met with senior officials, he outlined a key issue President Donald Trump had in the White House that he intended to solve by getting bad information into the hands of the president.
Kelly told officials that the information must flow through him, whether on paper or at meetings, because the president would make better decisions if good information was given to him."
Kelly’s diagnosis makes perfect sense, but others have tried and failed to tame Trump by monitoring his media consumption.
President Trump’s relationship with television goes back decades, and even now that he’s in the White House, his TV habits haven’t disappeared.
"If candidate Trump was upset about the dishonest media coverage, it was worth showing him that he was also covered fairly in affected publications," former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
Politico’s Tara Palmer wrote at the time that “according to six former campaigners, the key to managing Trump’s Twitter habits is to ensure that his personal media consumption consistently includes praise.”
All right.
But the idea that Trump’s Twitter habits have once been “controlled” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaigners know something the rest of us don’t know that Trump’s tweets would have been even more inflammatory without their interference.
We’ll probably never know about tweets Trump didn’t post.
If his assistants managed to get him out of trouble even a few times, their efforts were worth it.
But no one has been able to stop Trump from consistently creating controversy.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, where there are competing clicks, people are trying to promote their own interests, without exception, by providing Trump with material that supports their worldviews, but may not always be reliable.
In May, Politico wrote about the advisers’ tendency to present the president with strategically questionable information.
One example, described by reporter Shane Goldmacher, is as follows:
“Current and former Trump employees are saying Trump may be reacting explosively to negative press reports, especially damaging ones, by becoming obsessed with identifying their source.
That’s what happened in late February when someone gloatedly handed the president a printed copy of an article on the website GotNews.com, owned by Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, accusing Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the “source of multiple leaks” at the White House.
It doesn’t matter that Johnson has been permanently blocked from Twitter for taunting, or that he didn’t offer any concrete evidence, or that he has also made and retracted false accusations in the past.
Trump read the article and started asking subordinates about Walsh."
Goldmacher added that Reince Priebus, then chief of staff, and Rob Porter, head of the White House office, "have been trying to put in place a system to manage and document the documents that reach Trump."
How'd you do that?
Kelly tries to do the exact same thing three months later.
He may prove to be a more effective leader than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his aides are still competing for influence.
These unchanging factors make Kelly's mission very difficult.
Street musicians from abroad are not anxious to get permission to perform.
There are a lot of foreigners playing in the centre of Tallinn.
Those with whom Õhtuleht met admitted to playing in the Old Town without the permission of the city government.
We first found three street musicians near the Viru gates who had brought the same number of dogs with them.
It was clear that the musicians with dreadlocks and torn clothes were backpackers who could use a shower.
Despite appearances, the only woman in the company played a story with a fun rhythm on the accordion, while a man juggled with three balls next to her and called the passers-by closer.
The third man had sat next to them on a backpack and smoked a self-made joint in peace of mind.
Their three dogs did not allow themselves to be disturbed by the passing crowd.
Bob, who played the accordion and juggled the balls, said he was playing in the streets for fun and money.
The purpose of the group’s presentation was to collect ticket money for the ship travelling to Finland on the evening of the same day.
When asked if they asked permission from the city to make music in the Old Town, Noem and Bob shook their heads.
First of all, we didn't know.
Second, we never stay in one city for more than a day or two, and for the most part, permits are issued for a month or so.
There’s no point in paying for it,” Bob said.
When we got back to the gates of Viru about 20 minutes later, we saw two women staying with the musicians and driving them away.
The group moved to the Viru Centre intersection with backpacks and dogs to try their luck.
Three Polish young men also performed on Viru Street, one of whom played the violin, the other clarinet and the third had even brought along an electronic piano.
"We're here to entertain people, to spread music and joy, and to make money for fuel and living," the trio's pianist, Mivosh, explained.
According to Mivoshi, they are aware that the city government must have permission to perform.
"Of course we don't have it," he said jokingly.
But we hope that when people enjoy our music, there will be no problem.
Of course, if the police come, we'll go elsewhere, but we have to try," he added.
Eesti Pank bought 149 million euros worth of bonds as part of the public sector asset purchase programme of the central banks of the euro area in July, and the central bank’s bond portfolio grew to a total of 4.36 billion euros.
The central bank does not provide detailed information about the purchases.
The Governor of Eesti Pank, Hardo Hansson, has previously explained in response to the interpellation of the members of the Riigikogu that the asset purchase programme of the Eurosystem central banks includes three different purchase programmes: covered bonds, ABS and public sector bonds (PSPP).
The central bank buys bonds from the market to encourage investors who sell bonds to invest elsewhere.
As a result of the purchases, the return on the lower-risk assets decreases and this motivates investors to take greater risks.
As a rule, each central bank buys its own government bonds as part of a public bond purchase programme; bonds from other countries are not bought.
As the Estonian state has not issued any bonds, Eesti Pank makes so-called replacement purchases within the limits of the volume allocated to them.
Substitution purchases are also made by central banks in countries where the supply of purchase programme bonds is limited.
According to Hansson, Eesti Pank generally buys bonds from European institutions, such as the European Financial Stability Facility and the European Investment Bank.
Eesti Pank has been purchasing bonds under the asset purchase programme since March 2015.
Meanwhile, Elering bonds were also acquired, but Eesti Pank will no longer buy Elering bonds as of June 2016.
Starting from June, both Elering and Eesti Energia will acquire the bonds on behalf of the central banks of the euro area.
The travelers ignore the ditch and return to the "millionaire district"
Some of the wealthiest homeowners in the West Midlands are once again fiercely confronted by determined travelers who have defied a ditch dug by the council to reclaim a field away from their villas.
Travelers have parked their 20 caravans in a field near the wealthy "millionaires' district" christened Solihull Street.
They have returned with an army of horses, children, and trucks after they were kicked out of there only in May, without being disturbed by a trench dug by the council to prevent their invasion.
The tactical group found a weak spot in the guardrail, squeezing their vehicles through an unobstructed section that had been left as a footpath.
The furious residents have scoffed at Solihull's council, saying that the council is "useless in dealing with the problem".
An anonymous resident said: "They moved there Monday night after they were driven out of Bentley Heath, where they stoned passersby.
The council must be shamed into taking action because they are useless in dealing with the problem.
The travelers were there in May, they were driven away, and now they're back again.
There were more of them last night, probably even more today.”
He added, "Birmingham council knows how to handle this sort of thing by procuring long bars to protect their parks.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I'm not satisfied that I have to continue to pay the council tax if the council can't even stop such a thing."
A local resident, who also wished to remain anonymous, said, "This is ridiculous, we just saw the last of these travelers leave, and there's already a new offensive.
This time the number has increased and the grass has even been seen rumbling about the horse."
A spokesman for the Solihull Council said: "We are aware that there is an unauthorised campground on land near Streetsbrook Road, and we are working with the Solihull police. We are taking the necessary legal measures to get them moving as quickly as possible.
It is very helpful to have as many local residents as possible report any anti-social or criminal behaviour to the police by calling 101.
This will help create a picture of the situation for the court when we present the case to them."
The weekend will be visited by Minister of Culture Indrek Saar, among others, who is pleased that Estonia has been able to bring real top names to the world.
When asked why the Weekend Festival is so important for Estonians, Saar answers that it should be asked of all those who enjoy the festival to the fullest.
However, he admits that the real players have come to Pärnu.
“Looking at the level of the artists that have been brought to Estonia, they bring home the absolute top names of this genre of music – this often does not happen in our area,” the Minister of Culture said.
Which of the festival’s artists speaks for themselves the most?
