Of course, we also have our own Estonian makers: starting with NOËP and you can read a whole series of them.
In reality, this concentration of known names is very high," he says.
Take a closer look at the video!
Audi renews up to 850,000 diesel vehicles amid criticism from automakers
The day before Audi’s announcement, BMW said it would offer a software upgrade for more than 350,000 vehicles.
According to the BMW chairman, the company believes "there are smarter options than driving restrictions", referring to European cities, including BMW's hometown Munich, which has considered banning or restricting diesel vehicles.
Daimler announced on Tuesday that it will upgrade three million Mercedes vehicles in Europe to reduce diesel engine emissions.
None of the companies described these actions as a recall.
European car manufacturers have been keen to promote the use of diesel vehicles in Europe and the United States to help comply with the regulations on CO2 emissions.
However, nitrous oxide emitted by diesel engines is considered a carcinogen and can cause asthma.
At the same time, the cost of equipment to be installed for the automotive industry to neutralise the emissions of diesel vehicles will increase, making it difficult to keep the price of cars competitive.
While German automakers are under scrutiny, Chancellor Angela Merkel’s government is also accused of spoiling powerful automakers and ignoring signs of the problem.
The companies are trying to avoid repeating the mistakes of Volkswagen, which silenced the use of so-called “fraud devices” that allowed the emissions readings to be adjusted to conform with regulations while testing the car, but withdrew under normal driving conditions.
Several Volkswagen drivers have been charged in the United States and others are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
Last month, a former head of the thermodynamics division of Audi’s engine development division was arrested in Germany.
Former manager Zacchio Giovanni Pamio is Italian and therefore not protected from extradition and may face trial in the United States.
Earlier this year, Audi was drawn into a criminal investigation into Volkswagen in Germany, when the authorities accused the Audit of installing a system to circumvent European emissions requirements, thereby expanding the investigation, which had previously focused on the United States.
The inclusion of Audi in the investigation could be a major blow to Volkswagen as a luxury car manufacturer generates a disproportionate share of Volkswagen's profits.
20,000 euros worth of European Union flags will be purchased for Estonian schools.
The Ministry of Education plans to buy EU flags for Estonian schools by 1 September to mark the presidency.
A total of 570 educational institutions will receive the flag of the European Union with the dimensions of 105x158 cm.
The flags are meant to be displayed indoors, they must be made in high-quality printing technique indoors also with a tunnel mount, the news portal of ERR reports.
The flagpole sign reads: "A gift to Estonian schools to mark Estonia's first presidency of the Council of the European Union.
According to the Ministry of Education, the estimated cost of the 570 flags is 20,000 euros, i.e. one flag will cost 35 euros.
Journalist's murder highlights growing danger in Mexico
Workers from the weekly Riodoce usually gather on Wednesdays to review plans for the most recent chaos in Sinaloa, fueled by organized crime, corrupt officials, and incessant drug wars.
But today they are gathered in the shadow of a personal tragedy to discuss their own safety.
They are told that it is important to change your routine.
Two senior journalists are discussing which is safer: bringing the children to an office that was targeted by a grenade attack in 2009 or leaving them at home.
Security experts have written three words on the board at the front of the room: "enemies", "neutral", "allies".
They ask reporters to name names in each column without the need for evidence, enough with impressions and gut feelings.
