Dinosaurs used protective paint to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, although quite scary.
Scientists have now revealed the first findings of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner, which has been so well preserved that experts have described it as the "Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
It is so well preserved that it was even possible to identify that the skin covered by its scales was reddish-brown in color, and its past had been somewhat "difficult".
A report published in Current Biology described the creature as "the best preserved armoured dinosaur ever found" and "one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
The fossil is a new species of nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, 110-112 million years ago.
Its unbelievably good preservation overwhelmed researchers who describe it as "truly remarkable".
This armored vegetarian is the best-preserved type of fossil ever found, according to National Geographic magazine.
It was found on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk when he excavated at the Suncor Millenium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that did not resemble the surrounding rock, and decided to take a closer look.
The discovered fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The next six years were spent digging the animal out of a 2,500-pound (1,100-pound) piece of land.
After all this hard work, the end result is now finally ready to be made public.
"If you squint a little, you can almost believe he's asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum where the creature is exhibited.
"It goes down in science history as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
Studying his skin, researchers found that this herbivore, though covered in scales and reminiscent of a walking tank, was likely significantly threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
This armored dinosaur used red and white as protective colors to hide from predators and employed a form of shading known as counter-shadowing, which is also used by many animals today.
According to experts, this allowed the dinosaur to better blend into its surroundings and avoid enemies, as larger dinosaurs were likely hunting for it.
This 110-million-year-old creature from the Nodosaurus family first appeared on the news in May and is now on a visit to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Researchers have now studied the creature and named it after Mark Mitchell, a laboratory technician at the Borelopelta Markmitchell Museum, who was part of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours exposing the animal.
Due to the amazingly good preservation of the specimen, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the shape and size of the scales on the animal's body.
They discovered a counter-shelter, a method of protection common in the animal kingdom, meaning that the top half of the creature was darker than the bottom.
Although counter-sunk is common, the findings come as a surprise, as the Borelopelta are much larger than the animals that survive counter-sunk today.
This suggests that the dinosaur was being actively hunted by other carnivorous dinosaurs, that evolution preferred to shadow instead of confrontation as a survival tactic.
However, most modern animals using counter-espionage – such as deer, zebras, or armadillos – are much smaller and more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that nodosaurs had to really struggle to survive.
"The intense hunt for a huge, armored dinosaur shows just how dangerous the dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period could be," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of armored organic compounds also revealed that the dinosaur's skin was reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal to get clues about its life, including the preserved contents of its gut, to find out what the animal ate for its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river when it died, thus reaching the sea with the current, where it sank in front of its back to the ocean floor.
At the time, Alberta was as warm as today's South Florida, and rivers and oceans likely extended much further inland than they are today.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, while remaining three-dimensional, preserving its original shape," Brown said.
As a result, the animal today looks almost the same as it did in the Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use a lot of imagination to reconstruct it – you just have to squint your eyes and it feels like you’re sleeping.”
The Cretaceous Period was a time when huge two-legged carnivorous dinosaurs roamed the Earth - theropods.
Although their all king Tyrannosaurus rex lived millions of years later than Borelopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been hunted by some of its fearsome predecessors.
These include Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5 m) tall and six-ton-weight monster.
Scientists, whose recent findings have been published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borelopelta washed into the sea after death, and it mummified in mud.
The creature was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk when he excavated at the Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armoured dinosaur in the world, including the skin and scales, and is a complete muzzle to the hips.
These creatures averaged 18 feet (five meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
Its shoulders were pierced by two 20-inch spikes.
Scientists believe that this armor-covered herbivore ventured through present-day Western Canada until a flooded river washed into its open sea.
But the dinosaur’s undersea burial ground helped to preserve its scales in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the bumpy armour plates along the dinosaur skulls still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic: "This degree of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more incredible it seems.
The petrified remains of the skin still cover the bumpy scales on the animal’s skull.
The right forefoot rests beside him, and the five toes are extended upward.
I can count the scales on his soles."
How did an activist find the answer to the question "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell suffered a complete shock.
Just a day after traveling to New York City, this St. Louis resident sat on a bed in a rented room via Airbnb while browsing Facebook on his phone.
He came across a post from a former schoolmate.
It said, "The police just killed an 18-year-old kid and he's still lying on the street."
He was confused as to why no one else had posted this information on his feed, which is why he closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
The @TheePharoah user’s posts were repeatedly shared in his timeline.
The St. Louis rapper posted a live tweet about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man who was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying on the street, staying there for four hours.
"It's crazy," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new for him or his community.
He put his phone away, but later that evening saw another tweet announcing the gathering of people on Canfield Drive.
Photos of the police tape and screaming people and the man who claimed to be Brown's father and held up a sign saying "Ferguson's police just killed my unarmed son!" were shared.
He watched a live stream where a police officer stood with a barking dog in front of a group of protesters.
In the second video, another police officer, according to him, cocked a rifle and shouted, "I'm going to kill you all... animals."
Ferrell remembers how he caught himself thinking, "That's unusual."
"It's not the kind of murder we're used to and what we might call typical."
I was terrified at that moment.
I was angry and crying."
He booked a return flight and drove home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., he went to his father to pick up his six-year-old daughter and decided that they would drive to Ferguson by themselves the next morning.
What happened with Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the central theme of the new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will premiere in cinemas on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and tenacity from the perspective of the people who live in this community and who filled the streets demanding answers.
When Ferrell and her daughter - wearing a flowered dress and wearing a matching crown - drove up to Ferguson, they again talked about what they had talked about several times before that morning - the experiences and living conditions of black people.
"Do you remember when I taught you how the black community had to fight for its rights?" he recalls asking himself.
"We're driving Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that's not right."
"I couldn't not take him with me," Ferrell later said.
"What is happening now is the culmination of what has happened in the past.
He must know it, and see it, and grow in its midst.
He must learn about activism and organization, as well as about the different layers of black experience and living conditions and what we must do to become free and free ourselves.
Even if I manage to raise her without personally experiencing blatant racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would do him a disservice if I protected him from this world."
The first stop they made when they arrived in Ferguson was on the South Florissant Road, a place across the street from the police station that had become a kind of camp where activists were waiting for news of police officer Darren Wilson, who was ultimately not charged.
There Ferrell and his daughter joined forces with a local business owner who was preparing lunches.
They put food bags together and helped distribute them to protesters.
For Ferrell, a new type of activism was slowly beginning to take shape.
"My activism completely changed after August 9th," he said, noting that when he was a student at Missouri-St. Louis University, he was president of the Association of Minority Nursing Students and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
“I didn’t have any organizing experience.
It all just worked out."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, co-director of one of the films, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and film operator Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to document what was happening.
Ferrell asked, “Are you trying to document what’s going on, or are you trying to find a story that can be exploited?”
This kind of skepticism was the result of countless cases of people - often white - coming into the community and trying to take advantage of its pain and resilience.
Folayan explained in a recent interview: "We had heard that the voice of people born and raised in Ferguson would not be heard, and we wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had already struck hands with co-director Damon Davis, an area artist known for activism regarding death row inmates.
His involvement made the project appealing to Ferrell and six other locals who were watched for years by the crew of the film "Whose Streets?" after Brown's shooting.
"In this documentary, no one speaks for us or with us, but we speak for ourselves," Davis said.
"It was important to me how these people are portrayed, because that's how I'm portrayed."
Although the goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement was not about a "redemptive leader, but about a community reunion", as Folayan put it - he became the film's most open participant.
As a result, "Whose Streets?" documents surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and marrying his wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said, laughing at the first time he saw the finished film.
"But I realized that doing this job and humanising black people has to come with a certain vulnerability."
Furthermore, Ferrell's story emphasizes and re-emphasizes the role of black homosexual women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three startups who thought up the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter in the wake of the 2012 killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin on social media are homosexuals.
"Black homosexual women in leadership roles have maintained the movement overall," Ferrell said, " precisely because we have to fight on multiple fronts all the time.
Black homosexual women have to carry all that burden."
Folayan agreed, noting that "the movement is indeed being kept alive by black women and many of them are black homosexual women".
However, he claims that "it's not about some kind of equal opportunity thing" - Ferrell wasn't chosen as the center of the film because of his identity.
"He was the person who gave the right energy," he said.
"But it's no coincidence that she was right on the front lines, because there's a lot at stake as a black gay woman living in nodes like this.
His energy can be sensed through the screen."
Meanwhile, news cameras have long since disappeared from Ferguson, but racial ties between the community and the police remain fragile.
Ferrell faces a 2.5-year suspended sentence for blocking the road during the demonstration.
He describes the socio-political atmosphere in the area he calls home simply as a "huge threat".
Nevertheless, he still attaches importance to the mantra he has etched in his memory ever since he took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains."
