Start-ups to help your business avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but the polls were unprofitable.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse yet, misleading.
And even if he promised to ensure anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
"The system just wasn't consistent and objective," said Errett, who runs the 75-member San Francisco-based e-commerce company Madison Reed.
So he called for outside help.
New types of human resources start-ups are emerging to help companies figure out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software with the specific goal of measuring employee engagement, they enable companies to conduct sudden surveys, target specific teams and demographic groups, provide employees with anonymity and a hotline to complain, and in some cases, allow language carriers to bypass C-level managers and contact the board directly.
"Now there are tools like Strava and Fitbit designed to monitor health, but where's Fitbit for your business?" asked Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint, whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
According to Errett, in the three years he has been using Glint, he has gained a much better insight into what his employees think and feel.
In addition to surveys and surveys aimed at specific teams, it also offers a company heat map that gives an overview of which departments have the most complaints and which managers have the lowest support, allowing them to find out the reasons.
Businesses have come to realize they need to keep abreast of their work culture so as not to become the next Uber that has been engulfed in scandals since a former employee published a blog post describing a harrowing environment that penalized those who dared to speak out.
For startups like Glint, having an overview is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let’s Talk Payments, global governance, regulation and compliance could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Denver-based Convercent, a start-up based in Colorado that helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw an increase in interest and activity this year amid Uber’s dubious reputation.
Convertent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Uber recently registered as a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent lets companies send custom impulse surveys, collect confidential answers in real time, and view heat maps from problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous messaging line that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
And when it comes to the CEO, the complaints go straight to the board.
"Public opinion has usurped the regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
Quinlan said that if the company is found to be treating its employees badly or behaving unethically, the company could face serious consequences such as consumer boycotts, employee resignations and lawsuits, even if regulators do not intervene.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees at 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees are aware of the rules and operations and provide an easy way to interact with corporate headquarters.
If an employee wanted to report a problem earlier, he had to find the corporate headquarters' phone number or email address, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
This was often a daunting and uncomfortable process, said James Vitrano, general counsel for Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no good way to track employee complaints.
However, now that the company is using Convercent, problems such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair pay practices that did not reach managers who were operating in offices in other cities or states can be identified and dealt with more quickly.
“I’m able to get closer to the holistic 360-degree experience of employees,” said Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday’s Risk Management Team.
"And we will protect our shareholders from lawsuits with employees."
Quinlan said the companies began taking ethical behavior, values and employee engagement much more seriously in 2002, after audit firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations in connection with the Enron scandal.
However, it wasn't until "social media became mature" that companies realized they couldn't prevent their dirty laundry from washing publicly online.
"Before using technology to track ethical behavior, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a periodic fee for using their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity with the approval of venture capital investors who have been supportive of both start-ups.
In February, Convertent received $10 million in funding from Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, raising the total capital to $47 million.
Glinti invested $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, increasing the company's total funding to $60 million.
Such investments come as no surprise, given the interdependence between businesses, culture and venture capital.
More and more studies are showing that today’s employees expect more from the workplace than they did in the past.
In competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are merely stakes on the table.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy in the company, feel listened to, and that the work they do is rewarding, they are more committed to ensuring the company's success," said Nina McQueen, vice president of the Department of General Benefit and Employee Experience at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn income when the companies in their portfolio are doing well; companies are doing well when employees are engaged and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement and engagement, it’s no wonder they find support.
Having data on employee involvement is important, according to experts in work culture.
However, this data is useless if the company’s supervisors don’t do anything with it.
In fact, asking your employees for feedback can create expectations of change.
And if the changes do not happen quickly enough or not at all, it can lead to frustration and reduce employee involvement.
"If you ask 4000, you have to be prepared for 4000 conversations," said Russell Raath, president of Kotter International, a consulting and business management firm who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
"Because if things don't work out, the employees will think, 'Did you actually hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don’t care, why should I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly surveys among employees, has been able to take action on the same day that the problem has been reported through Glint.
And after receiving feedback from frustrated employees about the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, he was able to reorganize several teams in the company and provide communication training to deal with problems.
Ruby Tuesday, on the other hand, collects new employee data and is expected to lead to a longer-term commitment of employees in an industry known for its high workforce turnover.
