Rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent the Bill on Amendments to the Release into Environment of Genetically Modified Organisms Act (GMOVS) and the Plant Protection Act to the approval round.
With the amendment, the establishment of a separate database for the locations and handlers of genetically modified (GM) crops will be abandoned; in the future, the plant health register will be used for this purpose.
In addition, the obligation of a GM crop handler to have a prior agreement with a person engaged in beekeeping within the prescribed radius will be amended.
Although genetically modified crops are not grown in Estonia at the moment, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and non-modified crops.
At least until the decision to declare Estonia GMO-free has been made,” said Sigmar Suu, Head of the Plant Health Department of the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
"At the same time, it must be taken into account that the measures developed must be purposeful and proportionate, taking into account the costs and administrative burden for both the private and public sector," Suu added.
The Bill repeals the provisions relating to the database of locations and handlers of GM crops and the training in handling GM crops in the GMOVS, establishes the requirements for handling GM crops and commencement of economic activities.
Specific to beekeeping, the current obligation for GM crop growers to inform beekeepers about the start of GM crop cultivation will be replaced by the obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with the beekeeper before starting cultivation.
The Bill has been sent to the ministries for approval.
All interested parties have the opportunity to examine it in the draft information system and, if they wish, submit their opinion to the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
The planned changes will affect in particular the persons operating in the field of plant production, beekeepers and the Agricultural Board.
In the European Union, including Estonia, it is allowed to grow only one GM crop - MON 810 maize.
So far, however, no Estonian farmer has been interested in growing GM crops.
This is due to the fact that there is no corn pest in Estonia, the European corn borer, with respect to which the MON 810 maize line is resistant.
Also, varieties of this corn line have been bred for the southern regions, and this corn is not suitable for our climatic conditions.
In 2015 and 2016, the Ministry of Rural Affairs has commissioned studies to detect possible contamination with GM organisms in the seeds of different varieties of summer rape, maize and soy grown in Estonia.
Analysis of the samples taken showed that the seeds did not contain foreign genes and the study concluded that the seeds of rape, maize and soy varieties grown in Estonia do not contain genetically modified organisms.
From the above, it can be concluded that genetically modified crops are not grown consciously in Estonia, and it was also confirmed that there has been no accidental contamination.
