The White House exhibit cost taxpayers thousands.
According to military documents released to TIME magazine, the White House's decision to air a navy helicopter last month cost taxpayers as much as $24,000 to pay for an event marking American production.
The green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One during the president's onboarding, was the central attraction for the event, which took place at the White House on July 17.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials spent their tour looking at industrial products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-built helicopter was exhibited along with a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift made in Mississippi.
According to the documents of Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the White House War Office required the presence of a helicopter with a partial order, the FARGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed in the south yard for an "unusual" event.
"I wanted you to be aware of this because this is an unusually high-profile event," the HMX-1 commander said in an email to his commanding officer, the Navy's Deputy Chief of Staff, in the field of aviation.
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive in the southern yard at around 7 a.m. on July 17 and would remain there until the yard was cleared between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same evening.
Added to this was the fact that if leaving the White House were to be delayed, a second pick-up would be required for the return flight due to working time restrictions.
The original flight crew was at the helicopter at the time of the event, and squadron security personnel remained near the aircraft throughout its stay on the ground.
It was not possible to find out from the documents given to TIME magazine whether or not a second epic was needed in the end.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government assets for political purposes.
Documents indicate that HMX-1 was investigating whether the event could violate this provision.
"We asked if it violated Hatch's law, and we were told it didn't," the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have a choice," replied the deputy commanding officer.
The White House declared the event an "American-made" official event, and Hatch's law would not have covered it.
But even official events have political undertones.
The President supported the efforts of the health care reform discussed at the event in the Senate at the time and praised the efforts to keep government regulations in check.
The use of an aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically lucrative purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents have to use them to travel.
However, the requirement to use them purely for photosessions is unusual.
Trump came to attention in February when his first campaign event in Melbourne, Florida, featured a presidential plane, and his Twitter account was riddled with messages complaining about how his predecessor used the president's plane.
"The White House is very pleased with the display of 'America Made', featuring products from all 50 states made from American materials by American workers," White House spokeswoman Lindsay Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often conduct test flights around Washington, D.C., and in the southern courtyard, to practice dropping off the President of the United States at the White House with an inch of accuracy.
When Trump was in Germany at the G20 summit in early July, the HMX-1 held 58 tryouts in the White House courtyard.
According to the official, the flight was included in the “American-made” flight training standard for that month.
Squadron helicopters flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidential support missions."
According to the White House, no other exhibitors of the event burdened the taxpayer's wallet.
According to a representative of Sikorsky, the company was not involved in the organization of the exposition in the southern courtyard of the helicopter.
HMX-1 does not keep the budget documents of the presidential flights, and the exact costs caused by the event are difficult to ascertain.
But the Department of Defense's hourly compensation rate for FY2017 is $24,380 per flight hour.
The squadron's records indicated the length of the flight was from its main base at Naval Quantico Airfield in Virginia for 30 minutes in both directions.
The White House claims that the actual cost of using the helicopter is well below that amount.
"Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on estimated compensation rates is very misleading," Walters said.
"These estimated reimbursement rates include staff, maintenance and many other irrevocable costs to be taken into account for the annual appropriations."
According to a 2015 RAND survey, the compensation rates of the Ministry of Defence do not include personnel costs, but cover the costs of fuel, maintenance and contracts.
Former White House spokesman Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter at the event.
"The point is to show things made in America this week," Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and the State of Connecticut are very proud that they are contributing to our national security and that there are presumably hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I believe that, just like most Americans, we are all proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly on.
So, of course, it is right to highlight it."
It's unclear whether or not Trump encountered a helicopter as part of a tour of the event, but he did get behind the wheel of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump approached representatives of Sikorsky, making fun of media outlets about the company's products in his personal aircraft fleet.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I have three of their products."
