GMB worries about investments in McVitie's Glasgow plant
The union expects the executives of McVitie’s to confirm long-term production plans at the company’s Glasgow plant.
According to GMB Scotland, the company has been silent on the future of the investment at the Tollcross site.
The plant, which produces Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies and other products, employs more than 500 people.
The owner of the company McVitie's, Pladis, said they have invested more than £5 million in the object over the past few years.
Employees were hired there, and the union presidents "are the first to hear" when something changes in the factory's operations.
In a letter to the company’s site manager, GMB Scotland appealed to McVitie’s to “solve concerns that funding will not be used to modernize production lines.”
GMB Senior Managing Director Drew Duffy said: “The fact that we don’t get clarity from the site’s general manager on Tollcross’s business needs and future investment plan is causing our members deep concern.
Many generations of families have worked here, and the workforce is largely made up of the local community and the people of the area around Glasgow, an essential pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social exclusion.
Therefore, the eastern part of Glasgow desperately needs McVitie’s, a company with strong productivity growth in terms of jobs, wages and welfare, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living costs and a chronic decline in production.”
A spokesperson for Pladis said: "The Tollcross object manager received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday and the company will respond directly to him as we value active communication with employees and union representatives.
Two months ago, a regular meeting took place in Tollcross between employees and GMB representatives, where a number of issues were openly discussed.
We then discussed with the employees that, like all other companies operating in an extremely competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are reviewing our activities on an ongoing basis - and this applies to all our businesses and objects - to ensure that we are competitive.
He added: "Over the past few years, we have invested over £5 million in the Tollcross site, most of which has gone into production lines and operational improvements.
We fully understand Tollcross's legacy as a production site, and should there be any change in the site's operations, workers and union representatives will be the first to hear about it."
